GEOG 20H
Click box to close.      
Full Title: Field Studies in Surfing
Description: Field study methods from physical, human, and regional geography applied to surfing. Physical methods focus on coastal engineering: hydrographic surveys, wave measurement, etc. Human methods include spatial population distribution, attitude surveys, etc. Project or term paper, and presentation required.
PreRequisite: Concurrent enrollment in Geography 20.
College: L&S
Units: 1.0
Grading: Optional
Textbook Information: http://www.ucsbstuff.com/SelectTermDept.aspx

PreRequisite: Geography 3A.

GEOG 113
Click box to close.      
Full Title: The Alaskan and Arctic Environments Under Siege
Description: The purpose of this class is to learn about the geography of Alaska and the Arctic, including its history, climatology, oceanography, ecology, economics, and cultures. A variety of Alaskan and Arctic issues will be addressed, including indigenous people, climate change effects, natural resources, pollution, and political and military significance.
PreRequisite: Geography 3a or Earth Science 4.
College: L&S
Units: 4.0
Grading: Optional
Textbook Information: http://www.ucsbstuff.com/SelectTermDept.aspx

GEOG 115B
Click box to close.      
Full Title: Remote Sensing of the Environment 2
Description: Properties of satellite imagery and tools required to process data from remote sensing systems. Topics include spectral and spatial enhancement, image classification, geometric and radiometric correction, with emphasis on applications. Lab includes analysis of optical, thermal, Lidar, and radar data.
PreRequisite: Geography 115A with a minimum grade of C.

Units: 5.0
Grading: Optional
